[{"id":42077,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["$1$","$4$","$8$","$6$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Tension in string $B$ is due to the block of mass $2M$:<br><br>$T_B = 2Mg$<br><br>Tension in string $A$ is due to both blocks of mass $M$ and $2M$:<br><br>$T_A = Mg + 2Mg = 3Mg$<br><br>The elongation in a string is given by Hooke's law as $\\Delta L = \\dfrac{TL}{AY}$.<br><br>The ratio of elongations in string $A$ to string $B$ is:<br><br>$\\dfrac{\\Delta L_A}{\\Delta L_B} = \\left(\\dfrac{T_A}{T_B}\\right) \\left(\\dfrac{L_A}{L_B}\\right) \\left(\\dfrac{A_B}{A_A}\\right) \\left(\\dfrac{Y_B}{Y_A}\\right)$<br><br>Given that $\\dfrac{L_A}{L_B} = 2$, $\\dfrac{A_B}{A_A} = 1$, and $\\dfrac{Y_A}{Y_B} = 0.5 \\Rightarrow \\dfrac{Y_B}{Y_A} = 2$.<br><br>Substituting the values into the ratio equation:<br><br>$\\dfrac{\\Delta L_A}{\\Delta L_B} = \\left(\\dfrac{3Mg}{2Mg}\\right) \\times (2) \\times (1) \\times (2)$<br><br>$\\dfrac{\\Delta L_A}{\\Delta L_B} = \\dfrac{3}{2} \\times 4 = 6$<br><br>Answer: $6$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42146,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msqrt></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>T</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>T</mi></mrow><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>T</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>T</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>T</mi></mrow><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>T</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>T</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>T</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>T</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#8467;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42131,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Shearing stress&nbsp;is given by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>F</mi><mi>A</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>&#951;</mi><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mi>l</mi></mfrac></math></p><p>Thus, displacement is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>F</mi><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>A</mi><mi>&#951;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>18</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>4</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>60</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>9</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>48</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>48</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>&#956;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42105,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The formula for Young's modulus is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><mi>Y</mi></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mi>F</mi><mi>A</mi></mfrac></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>∆</mo><mi>l</mi></mrow><mi>l</mi></mfrac></mstyle></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mrow><mi>F</mi><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>∆</mo><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfrac></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>From above equation, it follows that</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Δ</mi><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>F</mi><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>A</mi><mi>Y</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>Again, volume of the wire is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>A</mi><mi>l</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>⇒</mo><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>V</mi><mi>A</mi></mfrac></math></p><p>Hence, from equation (1),</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>∆</mo><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>F</mi><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><msup><mi>A</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>Y</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>2</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>As, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Y</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi></math> is the same for both the wires,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>∆</mo><mi>l</mi><mo>∝</mo><mfrac><mi>F</mi><mrow><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>Hence, for two wires, it can be written that</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>∆</mo><msub><mi>l</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><mo>∆</mo><msub><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mrow><mo> </mo><msubsup><mi>A</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mfrac><msubsup><mi>A</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mrow><mo> </mo><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>3</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>As <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>∆</mo><msub><mi>l</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>∆</mo><msub><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>, from equation (3), it follows that</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo> </mo><msubsup><mi>A</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo> </mo><msubsup><mi>A</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>⇒</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mrow><mo> </mo><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msubsup><mi>A</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mrow><mo> </mo><msubsup><mi>A</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mn>16</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42082,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["2","1","4","5"],"answer":3,"solution":"Young's modulus: $Y = \\frac{\\sigma}{\\epsilon} = \\frac{F/A}{\\Delta L/L}$.<br>When the same force is applied and both wires stretch by the same extension $\\Delta L$, the ratio of Young's moduli is:<br>$\\frac{Y_A}{Y_B} = \\frac{F/A_A}{\\Delta L/L_A} \\times \\frac{\\Delta L/L_B}{F/A_B} = \\frac{A_B}{A_A} \\times \\frac{L_A}{L_B}$ <br>$=\\frac{4.5 \\times 10^{-5}}{3.0 \\times 10^{-5}} \\times \\frac{6.0}{5.4} = 1.5 \\times \\frac{10}{9} = \\frac{5}{3}$.<br>Therefore $x : 3 = 5 : 3$, giving $x = 5$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42108,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi>l</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>l</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Young&#39;s modulus is same for both the wires since the material is same.</p><p>For the first wire,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>f</mi><mi>L</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p><p>For the second wire,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>f</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>L</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>l</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><mi>i</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p><p>Dividing (i) by (ii)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>f</mi><mi>L</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>l</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>f</mi><mi>L</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>l</mi><mo>&#39;</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>l</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (15 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42136,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/08e890c3-7479-4415-9a6e-61ec9174973d-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 161px;\" /></p><p>From the above graph, we can find that when the strain is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;the stress is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>100</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MPa</mi></math>. We know that energy density is</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>U</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>stress</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>strain</mi></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>U</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>U</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>4</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>kJ</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42184,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Solids","question":"","options":["$0.2 \\mathrm{~J}$","$10 \\mathrm{~J}$","$20 \\mathrm{~J}$","$0.1 \\mathrm{~J}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Elastic energy $=\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\mathrm{F} \\times \\mathrm{x}$\n$$\n\\mathrm{F}=200 \\mathrm{~N}, \\mathrm{x}=1 \\mathrm{~mm}=10^{-3} \\mathrm{~m} \\quad \\therefore \\mathrm{E}=\\frac{1}{2} \\times 200 \\times 1 \\times 10^{-3}=0.1 \\mathrm{~J}\n$$","type":"mc